06631nam a22007575i 9780822376644DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20142014ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223766447 a10.1515/97808223766442doi  a(DE-B1597)552721  a(OCoLC)869578420  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1992.8.R43 7aPER0100302bisacsh04a791.45655  aMS 30102rvk0(DE-625)rvk/123653:00aReality Gendervision :bSexuality and Gender on Transatlantic Reality Television /cBrenda R. Weber. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (400 p.) :b32 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction Trash Talk: Gender as an Analytic on Reality Television -- tPART I. The Pleasures and Perils in Being Seen -- t1 The "Pig," the "Older Woman," and the "Catfight": Gender, Celebrity, and Controversy in a Decade of British Reality TV -- t2 Reality TV and the Gendered Politics of Flaunting -- t3 Keeping Up with the Aspirations: Commercial Family Values and the Kardashian Brand -- t4 When America's Queen of Talk Saved Britain's Duchess of Pork: Finding Sarah, Oprah Winfrey, and Transatlantic Self-Making -- t5 Wrecked: Programming Celesbian Reality -- tPART II. Citizenship, Ethnicity, and (Trans)National Ident -- t6 Abject Femininity and Compulsory Masculinity on Jersey Shore -- t7 Supersizing the Family: Nation, Gender, and Recession on Reality TV -- t8 "Get More Action" on Gladiatorial Television: Simulation and Masculinity on Deadliest Warrior -- t9 Jade Goody's Preemptive Hagiography: Neoliberal Citizenship and Reality TV Celebrity -- tPART III. Mediated Freak Shows and Cautionary Tales -- t10 "It's Not TV, It's Birth Control": Reality TV and the "Problem" of Teenage Pregnancy -- t11 Intimating Disaster: Choices, Women, and Hoarding Shows -- t12 Freaky Five-Year- Olds and Mental Mommies: Narratives of Gender, Race, and Class in TLC's Toddlers & Tiaras -- t13 Legitimate Targets: Reality Television and Large People -- t14 Spectral Men: Femininity, Race, and Traumatic Manhood in the RTV Ghost-Hunter Genre -- tBibliography -- tVideography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis essay collection focuses on the gendered dimensions of reality television in both the United States and Great Britain. Through close readings of a wide range of reality programming, from Finding Sarah and Sister Wives to Ghost Adventures and Deadliest Warrior, the contributors think through questions of femininity and masculinity, as they relate to the intersections of gender, race, class, and sexuality. They connect the genre's combination of real people and surreal experiences, of authenticity and artifice, to the production of identity and norms of citizenship, the commodification of selfhood, and the naturalization of regimes of power. Whether assessing the Kardashian family brand, portrayals of hoarders, or big-family programs such as 19 Kids and Counting, the contributors analyze reality television as a relevant site for the production and performance of gender. In the process, they illuminate the larger neoliberal and postfeminist contexts in which reality TV is produced, promoted, watched, and experienced.Contributors. David Greven, Dana Heller, Su Holmes, Deborah Jermyn, Misha Kavka, Amanda Ann Klein, Susan Lepselter, Diane Negra, Laurie Ouellette, Gareth Palmer, Kirsten Pike, Maria Pramaggiore, Kimberly Springer, Rebecca Stephens, Lindsay Steenberg, Brenda R. Weber   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aGender identity on television. 0aReality television programs. 0aSex role on television. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / Histor